# Requirement

Source task: `gourmania`

The generated interface should implement the following Vision2Web Level 2 frontend requirement.

I want to build a Gourmania culinary website. When someone opens the site, the first thing they see is a homepage with a welcoming banner, featured cookbooks including "The Brain Boosting Diet", "Healthy Helpings", and "The Silver Platter", and sections for "What's Cooking", "Favourite Holiday Recipes", "Recipe Categories", and "Browse Videos". The homepage displays favourite holiday recipes with images showing dishes like Gefilte Fish, Hamentaschen, Challah, and other recipes. Each recipe image on the homepage is clickable. If I click on a recipe image (such as Gefilte Fish), it takes me to the detailed recipe page showing ingredients, step-by-step instructions, and information about which cookbooks feature this recipe.

At the top of every page, there is a main navigation menu with links: "HOME", "RECIPES", "COOKBOOKS", "MY FOOD LINE", "MEDIA", "WHAT WE DO", and "NEWSLETTER". From the homepage, if I click on "COOKBOOKS" in the navigation menu, it takes me to the cookbooks page titled "MY COOKBOOKS" where I can see all of Norene's cookbooks displayed with their cover images, including titles like "The Food Processor Bible", "The Brain Boosting Diet", "The Healthy Jewish Kitchen", "Healthy Helpings", "The Silver Platter", and others.

From any page, I can click "MEDIA" in the navigation menu to access the videos page, which showcases cooking demonstrations organized into tabs: "ALL", "MY VIDEOS", and "RECOMMENDED". The videos include demonstrations like "Panic-Free Passover Cooking Demo", "Cooking Demo at Fruit of the Land – Tabbouleh Salad", "The Best Classic Cheese Noodle Kugel | JOY of KOSHER with Norene Gilletz", and "Norene Gilletz on Studio 4 with Host Fanny Kiefer". Each video has a thumbnail with a play button and links to video content.

The navigation menu does not have a standalone "Tips" link. Instead, to access tips, I need to click "WHAT WE DO" in the navigation menu, which takes me to a page titled "CULINARY SOLUTIONS" displaying professional services offered in a grid layout, including: Food Articles, Cookbook Editing and Indexing, Food Photography, Recipe Makeovers, Food Styling, Recipe Development, Food Consultants, and Nutrient Analysis / Food Labels.

All pages include links at the bottom to purchase books from Amazon, Amazon Canada (amazon.ca), and Indigo. The footer also displays social media icons for Facebook, Twitter, Instagram, and YouTube. Each page has a "NEWSLETTER" link in the navigation menu where users can subscribe to receive updates about cookbooks, recipes, and events.


